people, and their specific historical lineages, allows Aulino to show an inseparable link between forms of social organization and forms of care.Unlike most accounts of the "idian concerns of providing care in a rapidly aging society, Rituals of Care brings attention to corporeal processes. Moving from vivid descriptions of the embodied routines at the heart of home caregiving to depictions of care practices in more general ways-care for one's group, care of the polity-it develops the argument that religious, social, and political structures are embodied, through habituated action, in practices of providing for others. Under the watchful treatment of Aulino, care becomes a powerful foil for understanding recent political turmoil and structural change in Thailand, proving embodied practice to be a vital vantage point for phenomenological and political analyses alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBuddhismxSocial aspectszThailandzChiang Mai. 0aCaregiverszThailandzChiang Mai. 0aEthnologyzThailandzChiang Mai. 0aOlder peoplexCarezThailandzChiang Mai. 0aOlder peoplezThailandzChiang MaixSocial conditions. 0aPopulation agingxSocial aspectszThailandzChiang Mai. 4aAging. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  areligious studies, subjectivity, medical anthropology, moral anthropology, phenomenology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iT